1 Introduction
Because of environmental questions, the interest for developing the use of basic catalysts is increasing. (1, 2) One of the main drawbacks of these basic catalysts is that they are naturally polluted by water and carbon dioxide forming, by the way of an acidbase reaction, hydroxyl and carbonate groups on the catalyst surface. These adsorbates are usually considered as poisons of the reactivity even if they can be desorbed at specific temperatures depending on their nature and local environment. (3) In order to understand the catalytic properties of the basic catalysts linked to the pretreatment conditions, it is important to be able to characterize the adsorbates remaining on the surface before the catalytic reaction and, as a consequence, to know which basic sites are available after the thermal treatment.
Such an attempt has already been made with hydroxyl groups of magnesium oxide, (4, 5) which is a well-known basic catalyst involved in numerous studies of industrial interest. (3, 6-9) The aim of this article is to investigate, by a mixed experimentaltheoretical approach, the nature of the carbonates formed by interaction with CO2 on MgO surface defects and their stability upon thermal treatment. As CO2 is a Lewis acid, while H2O or methanol used in previous studies are Brnsted acidic molecules, the discussion of the results will involve a comparison between Lewis and Brnsted basic properties of MgO.
Infrared spectroscopy is one of the more informative techniques for the characterization of adsorbed molecules, (10) as carbonate species, formed on MgO surfaces. (11-19) The literature describes the carbonates present on MgO surface as monodentates or bidentates, but their detailed pictures have been unclear so far and the interpretation of IR band spectra, and their attributions in connection to specific adsorbed species are questions, which are far from being resolved. (2) In this work, using DRIFT spectroscopy, we have followed, for different temperature ranges, the interaction of CO2 with MgO powder sample, prepared by precipitation. The originality of the pretreatment operated here resides in covering the surface previously cleaned up from hydroxyl and carbonates groups by different amounts of CO2. In addition, we have attempted to specify adsorbed CO2 species by the ab initio DFT method. The theoretical investigation of CO2 interactions with the MgO surface has often concerned (100) flat surface, (20-22) step and corner defects. (20, 22, 23) Because of their lower stability compared to the (100) surface, the (110) (24) and (111) (23) lattice planes have attracted much less attention. Nevertheless, as the adsorption of molecules such as water or CO2 can modify the relative stabilities of the lattice planes, (25) this work presents results obtained on all these surfaces and also includes kinks and divacancies, which can be formed on the (100) surface.
In the following, the configuration and energetic stability as well as electronic structures of the different carbonate species that could be formed over MgO support are investigated using DFT calculations. In addition, by means of a thermodynamic model, the stabilities of carbonates are drawn as a function of temperature. Thus, the comparison of DFT calculated frequencies and measured IR data leads to a detailed description of the surface state depending on the temperature treatment.
2 Experimental and Computational Details
2.1 Materials and Experiments
2.1.1 Preparation of the Catalyst
Mg(OH)2 was obtained from Mg(NO3)2 (Aldrich, 99.99%) solution using ammonium hydroxide (Aldrich, 99%) (8 mol·L1) as the precipitating agent. Thus, the latter was added to a magnesium nitrate solution (1 mol·L1) and the pH value adjusted to 10 at 303 K. After stirring for 30 min, the precipitate was washed several times with deionized water and then filtered. The hydroxide sample was finally treated in vacuum (106 Torr) up to 1273 K (ramp 1 K·min1) and maintained at this temperature for 2 h.
2.1.2 Thermal Treatments
Figure 1 reports the different steps of the thermal treatments of the magnesium oxide sample. During the pretreatment phase, the sample is cleaned-up for 2 h at 1023 K under nitrogen flow (Air Liquide, U nitrogen >99.995% pure) (20 cm3·min1), then cooled down to 323 K. During the treatment phase, the sample is first contacted with carbon dioxide (Air Liquide, Alphagaz, >99.9% pure) diluted in nitrogen (5% in a 20 cm3·min1 flow) for 15 min. Then, it is once again heated at intermediate temperature (473 K < T < 1073 K) in a nitrogen flow (20 cm3·min1) for 2 h. In the following, only the final temperature T that determines the degree of carbonatation of the sample will be indicated.
Figure 1
Figure 1. Different steps of thermal treatment of the MgO sample.
2.1.3 Spectroscopic Measurement
DRIFT spectra were recorded on a Brker IFS 66 V spectrometer in the 4000600 cm1 range (4 cm1 resolution, 256 scans/spectrum) using a Thermo Spectra-Tech high temperature cell. All spectra were converted into KubelkaMunk units after subtraction of the spectrum recorded on dehydrated KBr sample. All spectra are recorded in situ after the pretreatment procedure described in section and the cooling down of the sample to 333 K. Finally, Raman spectra were recorded on a Model HL5R of Kaiser Optical System Inc. in the 3450100 cm1 range (4 cm1 resolution). It is equipped with a high-powered near-IR laser diode working at 785 nm.
2.2 Computational Details
2.2.1 Methods
All calculations were performed using the ab initio plane-wave pseudopotential approach as implemented in VASP. (26, 27) The generalized gradient approximation exchange-correlation functional of Perdew and Wang, PW91, (28) was chosen to perform the periodic DFT calculations with reliable accuracy on the convergence criteria. The one electron wave function was developed on a basis set of plane waves and the interaction between the core and the valence electrons is described by the projector augmented waves (PAW) approach. (29) The selected description of the oxygen atomic core allows a good convergence on the energy for a cutoff of 400 eV. The convergence criterion for the electronic self-consistent cycle was fixed to 106 eV per supercell. Geometry optimizations were performed within a conjugate-gradient algorithm until the convergence criterion on forces (102 eV·Å1) was reached. A dipolar correction along the perpendicular to the slab was applied in order to remove the effect of electrostatic interaction between the slab and its periodic images along the z axis. The adsorption energy of carbonates on the MgO surfaces was calculated as
