Vibrational spectra were calculated for selected surface species within the harmonic approximation. In addition to CO2 molecules, magnesium and oxygen surface atoms in direct interaction with adsorbed species were allowed to relax. The Hessian matrix was computed by the finite difference method followed by a diagonalization procedure. The eigenvalues of the resulting matrix lead to the frequency values. The assignment of the vibrational modes is done by inspection of the corresponding eigenvectors. A free carbon dioxide molecule is used as a reference in order to estimate the systematic deviation between experimental and calculated νCO values. The DFT calculated vibration frequencies for free CO2 are 2366 (2349), 1318(1340), and 637(667) cm1 (experimental frequencies (30) are indicated in parentheses). As the average of calculated frequencies fit the average experimental values quite well, no empirical scaling factors were applied to the DFT reported frequencies.
2.2.2 Surfaces
The computed models representing MgO (100) irregularities such as monatomic steps (S1), diatomic steps (S2), corners (C3), divacancies (D), and kinks (K), used in this work, were the same ones that were already considered by C. Chizallet and H. Petitjean et al. regarding the interaction of water (4, 5) and methanol molecules. (31) The MgO (100) terrace (T) involving five coordinated oxygen ions (O25C) was modeled by considering a slab formed by 5 layers where only the 3 topmost ones were allowed to relax during the optimization process. Each layer was formed by 8 MgO pairs and was separated from the other by optimized distance of 2.13 Å.
The MgO (110) surface consists of alternating rows of Mg and O ions. The slab was formed by 6 layers and only the 4 topmost layers were allowed to relax. The rows were 6 dMgO of length and were separated by an optimized distance of 3.01 Å.
The MgO (111) surface was modeled by repeated slabs of 12 layers. Because we are interested here into the formation of carbonate species by interaction of CO2 with the oxide surface, we have limited our investigation to the oxygen terminated rocksalt (111) surface model. The central 6 atomic layers (including 3 Mg and 3 O layers) were kept fixed in the structure optimization process, and the other topmost layers were free to relax. To avoid artificial surfacesurface interactions, the vacuum between the repeated slabs was fixed to 20 Å. We have tested that our optimized properties as surface atomic distances and interplanar distances between O and Mg close-packed (111) planes are in line with previous reliable models used in the literature. (32, 33)
The Brillouin zone integrations are performed on a Monkhorst-Pack 2 × 1 × 1 k-point mesh for the (100) surface and defects and 2 × 2 × 1 k-point mesh for the (110) and (111) surfaces. For MgO (100), (110), and (111) surfaces, we have checked that the calculated average surface energies for each surface orientation are comparable to literature values. (34-36) As expected, the calculated surface energy for the (111) facet was found to be relatively high (5.3 J·m2 (4.16 J·m2 (34))) compared to (110) facet (2.2 J·m2 (2.18 J·m2 (34))) and (100) facet (1.73 J·m2 (1.29 J·m2 (34))). This difference reflects well the instability of the polar terminated surface compared to the (100) one.
