3 Results and Discussion
3.1 Experimental IR Data
The effect of the pretreatment (1023 K, 2 h under N2) on the adsorbed species over the MgO surface is shown by the comparison of the DRIFT spectra of the initial sample and of the treated one (Figure 2). The considered high temperature process cleans up the surface from almost all hydroxides and carbonates. The IR spectra (black line) shows a weak remaining absorption band at 3750 cm1, which is attributed to strongly bounded hydroxides, (5) and some carbonates with IR bands at 1657 and 1329 cm1.
Figure 2
Figure 2. DRIFT spectra of the adsorbed species over magnesium oxide before (red line) and after (black line) pretreatment at 1023 K (arbitrary unit for absorbance).
After the addition of CO2, DRIFT data show strong modifications in the IR range 18001000 cm1. Figure 3 gathers the set of IR spectra obtained after the surface treatments at temperatures T = 523 K, 673 K, and 873 K. As expected, the spectra show the formation of carbonate species, the amount of which decreases upon the successive thermal treatments. After the treatment at 873 K, the obtained spectra show the same absorption in the 10002000 cm1 range as the one recorded after the pretreatment at 1023 K. In addition, the successive thermal treatments (T) do not affect the recorded high frequencies (>2000 cm1) on the magnesium dioxide surface. In the lower frequency ranges, the absorptions are always very high due to the bulk infrared absorption of MgO with a lateral phonon frequency at 800 cm1. (38)
Figure 3
Figure 3. Recorded DRIFT spectra of the adsorbed species over magnesium oxide after CO2 adsorption under inert gas for different T treatments (arbitrary unit for absorbance).
According to the literature, adsorption of carbonate species leads to the splitting of the ν3 stretching vibration band of the free ion, located at 1415 cm1, and gives different contributions depending on the geometry of the adsorbed ion. (2, 13) The carbonate ν3 stretching mode is split to ν3high and ν3low contributions. Generally, a consensus is gained that the more coordinated the carbonate ion, the more split the two contributions. In addition, the average Δν for each species has also been determined. (13) As reported in Table 1, which summarizes the IR results from numerous experimental studies, the vibrational frequency bands recorded on magnesium oxide surfaces have been assigned either to monodentate, bidentate, or hydrogen carbonate species. (11, 12, 14-16, 18) This table also evidences many discrepancies relative to the IR values assigned to different carbonate species, which may be due to the different states of the MgO surfaces obtained after the thermal treatment such as hydration state, morphology, etc.
