In this work (see Figure 3), the MgO surface is almost free of residual adsorbates. Therefore, no hydrogen carbonate can be found on the surface even at T = 523 K (no contribution at 1220 cm1). Comparing the position of our recorded spectra with IR attributions reported in Table 1, one can assign, at first sight, all the identified bands in the range of 13701590 cm1 to monodentate species and those in the ranges of 12701390 cm1 and 16201710 cm1 to bidentate species. Moreover, two minor contributions located at 1252 and 1275 cm1do not change with the thermal treatment and can be linked to the small amount of silicon, which is a residual impurity in the sample. This attribution of the carbonate bands goes on line with the evolution of the spectra with T: the most stable species are reported as bidendate (11) and are the only ones remaining on the MgO surface after a treatment at 873 K, giving contributions at 1661 cm1 and 1321 cm1. Nevertheless, for each carbonate species, several contributions are obtained. For instance, in the infrared range attributed to bidentate species, two bands at 1680 and 1651 cm1 (split bands at 1321 and 1304 cm1) can be attributed to two different bidentate species. The same analysis can be made with the monodentate species. These different contributions are probably linked to the carbonate formation on different MgO defects. Because in catalytic applications these defects may behave differently, (39-41) it is important to know which of them are poisoned by carbonates as a function of the thermal treatment process. Modeling is thus necessary to calculate the theoretical position of the IR band linked to carbonate species depending on their topological environment.
3.2 Computational Results
3.2.1 On the Nomenclature of Carbonates
The earlier work of Fukuda and Tanabe (11) described the carbonates as bidentate or unidentate for the carbonate linked with only one magnesium ion and bridging for the one bonded with two magnesium ions (see Scheme 1). Busca and Lorenzelli (13) added some complexity to this model by considering polydentate species. The improvement in the description of the carbonates by the way of computational methods allows us to give a more precise description of the carbonates. Those carbonates should be given an unambiguous name. We propose that the carbonates should be ranked by the number of oxygen atoms making connection with the surface (ionic or covalent bonds), such connections being the bonds that lengths are less or equal to the MgO bond length in the bulk magnesium oxide (2.1 Å). Let us add that a thorough description of the nature of carbonate bonds will be evaluated through DFT electronic analysis. Thus, mono-, di-, and tridentate carbonates refer, from now on, to carbonate species in which one, two, and three oxygen atoms are connected to the surface, respectively. In addition, among a general type of carbonate species, for example, bidentate, distinctions will be made considering the type of plane or surface defect on which the interaction occurs. The carbonates will be named by the combination of a letter for each type (M, monodentate; B, bidentate; T, tridentate) and of the name of defect or plane. For instance, T-S1 will refer to a tridentate carbonate formed on a S1 step, and M-(111) will refer to a monodentate carbonate on a (111) plane.
