3.2.2.1 Adsorption on the Flat Surface
The low calculated adsorption energy (0.09 eV) for a linear CO2 molecule on flat (100) terraces T confirms that five coordinated O25C ions of MgO surface are totally unreactive for the formation of carbonates in agreement with literature data. (21, 42)
3.2.2.2 Adsorption on Surface Defects
DFT calculations of CO2 interactions with four and three coordinated oxygen ions (O24C and O23C), involved in the defects of the MgO(100) plane, show largely more stable adsorbed carbonate species compared with flat MgO(100), (Table 2). Pacchioni has investigated the interaction of CO2 on regular and defect sites of the MgO(100) surface by means of ab initio cluster model SCF calculations. (42) He explained that because of the considerably large Madelung potential of a surface five coordinated oxygen ion (O25C site) compared to the lower coordinated site as the four coordinated O24C sites, the electron cloud of the O24C ion is more spatially diffuse and can easily overlap with the CO2 empty orbitals interacting with the surface.
DFT optimizations predict that the CO2 molecule adsorbs with energy values of 2.26 and 2.16 eV on the S1 and S2 step systems, respectively (Figure 4a,b). The molecule interacts with O24C ions with an average dCO distance of 1.37 Å and assumes an orientation parallel to the edge, which allows a direct electrostatic interaction of its O atoms with the Mg2+4C cations of the surface. The OCO angle is predicted to be of about 130. These results are in line with those of Olsbye and co-workers (20) who have called a similar configuration of adsorbed carbonate species as monodentate. Nevertheless, as in a such configuration, the carbonate species forms three connections (short bonds < 2.10 Å) with the MgO surface (one O2 is already inserted in the magnesium oxide network (Oβ) and two Mg2+ are linked to the oxygen ions (Oα) of CO2). Thus, we propose (see section ) to call them tridentate carbonates (T-S1 and T-S2).
