The calculated Hessian matrix (Table 2) of the adsorbed tridentate species indicates wavenumbers of 1603 cm1 (T-S1), 1639 cm1 (T-S2), and 1300 cm1 (T-S1), 1287 cm1 (T-S2) for ν3h and ν3l, respectively. As shown in Table 3, these later frequencies are affected by the presence of the second and the third neighboring carbonate surface (θ = 2/3 and θ = 1 ML). Thus, compared to the case of isolated carbonate, the calculated vibrations vary by less than 100 cm1 for θ = 2/3 ML and highly change for the monolayer coverage. The split between low and high frequencies grows when the coverage increases, due to the coupling between the adsorbed carbonates sharing a Mg2+ cation. Similar results were also observed for CO2 adsorbed on the ZnO surface. (45)
Considering these results, the experimental bands (Figures 2 and 3) observed around 1660 and 1320 cm1, that remain clearly visible whether the temperature is considered, can be attributed to single tridentate species strongly attached on the step defects of the magnesium oxide surface.
The modeled corner, kink, and divacancy systems (Figure 4ce) involve a three coordinated ion O23C, which interacts directly with the adsorbed CO2 molecule. On these sites, the adsorption energy of carbonate species are found to be lower than on the four coordinated sites. The analysis of the distances between Oα and the surface (Table 2) show that carbonates are doubly bounded to the surface through the network oxygen (Oβ) and one oxygen atom (Oα) from CO2. The bond character of these bidentate carbonates (B-C3, B-K, and B-D) can be analyzed from the charge density difference graphic represented in Figure 5. On the kink (the same trend is observed for divacancy (not represented)), the adsorption does not strongly modify the slab. The electron rich zones appearing into O2p orbitals indicate only one polar covalent bond between (Oα) from CO2 and Mg2+4C. The electron rich zone around the third oxygen atom, the (Oγ) of the carbonate molecule, is orientated out of the plane, and thus, that oxygen does not make any connection with the surface. On the corner, the interaction of B-C3 induces a strong modification on the substrate. The surface oxygen atom (Oβ) is strongly displaced in order to ensure the double connection of carbonate species with the surface. IR νCO (ν3hν3l) frequencies of carbonates adsorbed on corners, kinks, and divacancies are calculated to be of 17271198 cm1 (B-C3), 16791125 cm1 (B-K), and 16491149 cm1 (B-D), respectively. These resulted values can predict that the experimental band observed at 1680 cm1 on the sample treated at T = 523 and 673 K is the signature of bidentate carbonate species adsorbed on corner, kink, and/or divacancie defects. The ν3l band frequencies are out of the range of this study. As there is only one adsorption site, the effect of coverage is not considered here.
Finally, it remains the question of the observed IR bands between 1350 and 1600 cm1 (namely, located at 1516 cm1, 1423 cm1, and 1367 cm1) for the sample treated at T = 523 and 673 K, which cannot be explained by the presence of carbonate species on the MgO(100) defects. Moreover, Yanagisawa et al. (14) have already considered the adsorption of CO2 on cubic crystallites of the MgO smoke, which exhibit well-defined (100) facets, and they have not observed any IR adsorption between 1350 and 1600 cm1. This means that the recorded IR frequencies on our samples would result from different adsorption configurations on other crystallographic planes even if they are known to be less stable in vacuum conditions compared to the (100) plane. In fact, several theoretical (34, 46, 47) and experimental (48) studies have shown the change in the stability of surface orientations after the addition of adsorbates such as water. As IR spectroscopy showed that, in our conditions, few OH groups remain on the surface, we investigate, in the following section, the adsorption configurations and properties of CO2 on faceted (110) and (111) surfaces of MgO.
3.2.3 CO2 Species Adsorbed on MgO(111) and (110) Surfaces
In Figure 4f,g is reported the configurations of carbonate species formed over the modeled MgO(111) and (110) surfaces, respectively. As shown in Table 2, the most energetically stable species (2.75 eV) is formed over the MgO(110) surface. Over this plane, the orientations as well as the geometry of carbonates are similar to T-S1 and T-S2; thus, this carbonate is called tridentate T-110. Therefore, while the charge density difference graphic (Figure 5) shows a similar isosurface shape for the electron rich zones of tridentate species, the adsorption is energetically favorable, by 0.49 eV, on the (110) than on the stepped (100). The vibrational frequency calculations of T-110 indicate values at 1559 and 1331 cm1 for the νCO3h and νCO3l, respectively. This carbonate type may correspond to the species vibrating around 1510 and 1360 cm1 on our sample treated at T = 523 and 673 K.
As for the stepped (100) surface, in the presence of neighboring carbonates, the νCO values strongly vary, and the split between low and high frequencies of T-110 grows as the coverage increases (Table 3).
Over the (111) surface terminated by oxygen atoms, the carbonate lies on the surface through a single connection. Thus, the carbonates adsorb as monodentate species on the MgO(111) surface. In spite of the short dCO(β) bound distance of 1.31 Å, which is the same as that for the tridentate configuration, the small OCO angle of 115 illustrates the repulsive interactions that undergo between the oxygen atoms (Oγ) and the surface (Figure 4g). These repulsive interactions can clearly be attested in Figure 5 by the charge density difference on M-111 configuration that evidence the low electron density between (Oγ) and the surface. This may explain the low energetic stability of these species. In addition, as the carbonate presents a symmetry close to D3h, the split between νCO3h and νCO3l is very low: 1440 and 1378 cm1 (1415 cm1 for the free carbonate (49)). These values are smaller than the frequency values calculated by Allen et al. (23) who predicted vibrational frequencies for adsorbed carbonates on the MgO(111) surface in the ranges of 14401459 and 15721631 cm1. This is probably due to the empirical method used by these authors. In this work, the resulted monodentate carbonate, with a weakly degenerated IR band, could be attributed to the species vibrating at 1423 cm1 on the DRIFT spectra for the sample treated at T = 523 and 673 K. Nevertheless, the low bonding energy of 0.8 eV is not consistent with the persistence of the IR bands for high temperature treatments. This point will be discussed in the next section. In Table 3 are also reported the adsorption energies and νCO frequency values of carbonate M-111 for increasing coverage. The high coverage was not reached because of the strong repulsive interactions occurring between surface/carbonates and carbonate/carbonate species. Thus, as depicted in Table 3, for coverage of 3/4 monolayer, the adsorption is highly endothermic, and the calculated frequency values are highly different from those of single carbonate calculations.
3.2.4 Adsorption Thermodynamics
In order to get a more precise picture of the respective stabilities of adsorbed carbon dioxide on different planes and defects and more particularly, to determine the temperature of desorption of the different adsorbed carbonates, the Gibbs free adsorption energy diagram was plotted for each considered system (see Figure 7). The partial pressure is set to 0.001 Pa, and the desorption is presumed to occur when the Gibbs free adsorption energy becomes positive.
