Figure 7. Gibbs free energy diagrams (kJ/mol) at a constant pressure (PCO2 = 0.001 Pa) as a function of temperature (K) for adsorbed carbonates on different MgO surfaces and defects.
As reported in Figure 7, Gibbs free adsorption energies of carbonates follow the same linear trend. On the (100) plane, the bidentate carbonate species that populate the corners, kinks, and divacancies are predicted to leave the MgO support for the temperature range of 722822 K. Tridentate carbonates formed on the Mg(100) steps would desorb at higher temperature and remain on the surface for temperatures as high as 908 K. This is in agreement with the assignment we made for the IR bands recorded at T = 873 K for the highly adsorbed tridentate species
The same kind of tridentate species is also strongly adsorbed on the (110) surface and thus should not disappear at T < 1200 K, but experimentally, it is shown that the corresponding IR bands (1516 and 1367 cm1) disappear from the spectrum at 673 < T < 873 K. We suppose that this contradiction may be explained considering the well-known stability of the (100) surface compared to the (110) surface: surface recombination may thus occur at T < 873 K, leading to the disappearance of the (110) plane and to the desorption of these species at lower temperature than predicted by our thermodynamic calculations. Moreover, the surface reconstruction of the (110) planes into the reconstructed stepped (100) surface (50) may also explain the enhancement of the IR adsorption at 1321 cm1 assigned to T-S1. Let us add that this reconstruction phenomenon should be confirmed by an appropriate kinetic study.
Finally, on the (111) surface, the desorption of monodentate carbonates is predicted to occur at 314 K. Regarding this result, the IR band observed at 1440 cm1 for temperature as high as T = 673 K can not be attributed to the monodentate species. Du and co-workers have attributed similar infrared recorded bands of νCO3h = 1445 cm1 and νCO3l = 1375 cm1 to bulk-like carbonates, which could desorb at high temperature. (19) Mekhemer et al. (17) have reported a similar suggestion. In order to characterize such carbonates, we have performed Raman spectra on a sample treated at 673 K. Nevertheless, no absorption band at 1100 cm1, characteristic of the ν1 Raman active bulk carbonates, (51, 52) was observed on this sample. As bulk carbonates can be present but their amount may be under the detection limit of the Raman spectrometer, a conclusion on that point is difficult to be made.
3.3 New Insights on Basicity Characterization
As underlined in the introduction, in order to study the catalysis, we need to know the nature of the basic sites available after the pretreatment step. For that purpose, the data obtained in this study on carbonate species, their nature, localization, desorption temperature, and IR vibration bands (calculated and experimentally detected), are summed up in Table 4. The new nomenclature of these species is also reported in order to take into account not only their mono-, bi-, or tridentate character but also the topology of their adsorption site.
