Moreover, the literature dealing with basic catalyst reactivity shows that the characterization of the basic sites is a key point for the interpretation of the catalytic results. One of the most popular methods to determine these basic properties is CO2 TPD that consists of following the progressive desorption of preadsorbed CO2 with increasing temperature (see as an example, Hattoris review (53)). An attempt to discuss the relevance of this method has already been made (54) underlining that CO2 adsorption probes the Lewis basic character of the surface, whereas Brnsted basicity is mainly involved in a catalytic reaction. Let us remind that Lewis basicity is the ability of the surface to give an electronic pair to a Lewis acid molecule, while Brnsted basicity is, according to Brnsted definition, (55) the ability to deprotonate a molecule. It implies that all Lewis bases are also Brnsted bases and reciprocally, but we demonstrate here, in the particular case of oxides ions, that the strength scale is different depending on the nature of the considered basicity.
This demonstration is made from the comparison of the deprotonating adsorption energy of water (a Brnsted acid) and the formation of the Lewis adducts of CO2 (a Lewis acid) on MgO(100) plane defects. Using a similar theoretical approach, C. Chizallet and co-workers have established the desorption temperature of H2O from the MgO (100) defects. According to these authors, water leaves S1, K, D, and C3 defects at temperatures of 620 K, 805 K, 1110 K, and 740 K, respectively. (4) Thus, it can be seen that the strongest interaction between water and the surface is achieved on kinks and divacancies, whereas the most stabilizing sites for CO2 adsorption are predicted here to be the steps. By consequence, direct correlation between the information obtained by CO2 TPD and a reaction in which the first step is deprotonation has to be made very cautiously.
4 Conclusions
Attribution of the IR bands of the carbonates adsorbed on MgO is a very important tool to identify the nature of the active basic sites available after a pretreatment. DFT calculations combined with the DRIFT measurement on the MgO sample after peculiar pretreatments allow us to give a new assignment to these IR bands considering the adsorption on (100) defects and (110) and (111) planes. These attributions are confirmed by the thermodynamic calculations of the stability of all carbonate species. Moreover, these results give a new tool to identify the crystallographic plane and defects by analyzing the formation of the IR band when absorbing the CO2 on it. Results show that the strongest basic site versus CO2, which is a Lewis acid, is not the same as that of the strongest basic site for the deprotonating adsorption of Brnsted acids. Thus, even of the same nature, Lewis and Brnsted basic sites differ by their basicity strength scale. This conclusion should have consequences on the use of CO2 TPD when it has to be correlated with kinetic studies of basic Brnsted reactivity.
